Translation

Most translation systems operate like

Word
→
Word

Pantheon instead aims for

Semantic Volume
→
Invariant
→
New Language

The invariant survives even if every word changes.

This is similar to translating:

* mathematics into music
* architecture into software
* mythology into engineering
* biology into computation

The representation changes while the underlying structure is preserved.

⸻

Semantic Integral

Think of communication as

\text{Meaning}=\int_{\text{conversation}} f(\text{signal},\text{context},\text{timing},\text{shared knowledge})\,dt

Every sentence contributes a tiny amount.

No sentence contains the whole meaning.

Only the accumulated integral does.

⸻

Compression Quality

Pantheon could measure compression by asking:

Does the compressed form reconstruct nearly the same semantic volume?

High compression:

1 sentence
↓
20 pages reconstructed

Poor compression:

1 sentence
↓
Only itself

⸻

Translation Quality

A translation succeeds if

Volume(original)
≈
Volume(reconstructed)

even when

Words(original)
≠
Words(reconstructed)

This is the same principle behind preserving an algorithm across programming languages or a melody across different instruments.

